{{use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} {{use Indian English|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox religious biography | honorific-prefix = [[Acharya]] | name = Aryanandi | image = | caption = | religion = [[Jainism]] | sect = [[Digambara]] | official_name = Acharya Aryanandi | birth_name = Shankar | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1907|2|28}} | birth_place = [[Dhorkin]], [[Paithan]], [[British India]] (now [[Aurangabad District, Maharashtra|Aurangabad district]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]) | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2000|2|8|1907|2|28}} | death_place = [[Navagad]], [[Parbhani]], [[Maharashtra]] | parents = Laxmanrao, Krishnabai Ahmindra | initiation_name = Aryanandi | initiator = Muni [[Samantabhadra (Jain monk)|Samantabhadra]] | initiation_place = [[Kunthalgiri]], [[Maharashtra]] | initiation_date = 13 November 1959 | website = {{url|http://aryanandiseva.com}} }} {{Jainism}} [[Acharya]] '''Aryanandi''' was a prominent [[Jain monk]] of the early 20th century. He is best known for his work in establishing several Jain schools in the Indian state of Maharashtra.<ref name="google1" /> Several Jain monks before him have also been named Aryanandi.<ref name="nam" /><ref name="granth" />
==Biography== Acharya Aryanandi was born in the village of Dhorkin, [[Paithan]], [[Aurangabad District, Maharashtra|Aurangabad district]], [[Maharashtra]], India.<ref name="ellora" /><ref name="seva" /> He has been the only [[Jain acharya]] from the [[Saitwal]] community in recent times.
==Contributions== He was held in high esteem and is best remembered for the setting up of several Jain schools in Maharashtra,<ref name="google1"/> including the Acharya Arya Nandi Lecture Hall in [[Ellora Caves|Ellora]], [[Aurangabad District, Maharashtra|Aurangabad district]], Maharashtra.<ref name="pushp" /> The Jain Gurukul at Ellora was also established by him.<ref name="data" /><ref name="gurukul" /> The noted German Jainologist, Hermann Kuhn, studied [[Jain scriptures]] extensively under the tutelage of Acharya Aryanandi.<ref name="benadi" /><ref name="samaj" /> Acharya Aryanandi is also known as Tirthrakha Shiromani for his inspiration to make one crore rupees fund in preservation of Jain tirthas.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}
