{{Infobox cave | child = | name = Baxian Caves | other_name = 八仙洞 | alt_name = | photo = Bashian Caves 02.jpg | photo_width = 250px | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | map = <!-- or | map_image = --> | map_width = | relief = | map_alt = | map_caption = | label = | label_position = | mark = | mark_width = | location = [[Changbin, Taitung|Changbin]], [[Taitung County]], [[Taiwan]] | grid_ref_UK = | grid_ref_Ireland = | grid_ref = | coords = | coords_ref = | depth = | length = | height_variation = | elevation = | discovery = | geology = [[Sea cave]] | entrance_count = | entrance_list = | difficulty = | hazards = | access = | show_cave = | show_cave_length = | lighting = | visitors = | features = | translation = | language = | pronunciation = | survey = | survey_format = | bcra_grade = | registry = | free_label_1 = | free_data_1 = | website = | embedded = }}
'''Baxian Caves''' ({{zh|c=八仙洞|p=Bāxiān Dòng}}) are [[sea cave]]s located in the east coast of [[Changbin, Taitung|Changbin Township]], [[Taitung County]], [[Taiwan]].
==History== Recently, the caves have been occupied and used as temples or places to place cremation ashes. However since 10 years ago, the Cultural Heritage Preservation Act was promulgated, subsequently the Taitung County Government, East Coast National Scenic Area and Changbin Township Office had been trying to take over the caves. On 22 November 2017, they finally managed to take back the last cave and completed the reclamation of all 30 saves in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3304059|date=22 November 2017|title=Taiwan’s Taitung County reclaims the last occupied cave of the country’s oldest prehistoric site|publisher=Taiwan News|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>
==Geology== Baxian Cave possesses a distinctive eroded look and is famous for ruins dating from the [[Old Stone Age]]. There are 10-plus caves on the {{convert|328|ft|m|disp=flip}} high precipice, each of a different size and depth. Originally the caverns were below sea level, allowing waves to shape them, but now they are located on a high cliff—proof of the East Coast's changing surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastcoast-nsa.gov.tw/en-us/Attractions/Detail/70 |title=Baxian Cave |work=East Coast National Scenic Area |publisher=ECNSA Headquarters |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321182756/http://www.eastcoast-nsa.gov.tw/en-us/Attractions/Detail/70 |archivedate=2016-03-21 |df= }}</ref>
