{{islam by country}}
[[Image:Togo Mosque.jpg|thumb|left|Mosque in northern Togo]]
'''[[Muslims]] in [[Togo]]''' represent between 12 and 20% of the national population. [[Islam]] came to Togo about the same time as it did much of [[West Africa]]. The vast majority of Muslims in Togo are [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] of [[Maliki]] school of [[jurisprudence]].<ref>CIA=Togo</ref>

==History==
Islam was first introduced into West Africa south of the [[Sahara]], across the salt and gold trade routes. Islamicized [[Berber people|Berber]] and [[Tuareg people|Tuareg]] merchants traveled the trans-Saharan trade routes. As time passed, Muslim clerics and scholars — teaching their beliefs and setting up places of worship along the routes — accompanied traders on their journeys. The [[Hausa people|Hausa]] and the [[Fulani people|Fulani]], a traditionally nomadic group, traveled all over West Africa, taking their Muslim beliefs to places such as present-day [[Guinea]], [[Sierra Leone]], and [[Liberia]].

==Demographics==
Estimates on the number of Muslims in Togo vary depending on the source. The [https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/to.html#People CIA World Factbook] puts the figure is 20%. A survey by the [[Pew Research Center]] gives an estimate of 12.2% of the population or 809,000 individuals as of 2009.<ref>{{Citation|editor-last=Miller |editor-first=Tracy |date=October 2009 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |title=Mapping the Global Muslim Population: A Report on the Size and Distribution of the World’s Muslim Population |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] |url=http://pewforum.org/newassets/images/reports/Muslimpopulation/Muslimpopulation.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010050756/http://pewforum.org/newassets/images/reports/Muslimpopulation/Muslimpopulation.pdf |archivedate=2009-10-10 |df= }}</ref>

==Notable Muslims==
* [[Mohamed Kader]], first [[Togo]]lese player to score in [[Fifa World Cup]].

